To avoid detection of a pseudo-photocurrent, which is explained in detail below, the pH of Synechocystis cell suspensions was always confirmed and adjusted when necessary prior to electrochemical measurements. The pH of the suspension preferably should be below approximately 8.0, and should never be above 8.5. Otherwise, the buffering capacity of TES (pH 6.8–8.2) is outcompeted by drastic changes (increases) in the pH of the medium due to photosynthesis76–78, resulting in detection of a pseudo-photocurrent of the following reaction:1Mn2++2H2O⇌MnOOH+3H++e−\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
